    <div id="block-miller-page-title" class="miller-title-wrapper">
  
    
      
  <h1><span>April 20, 1961: Special Message to the Congress on Taxation</span>
</h1>


    <div class="share-trigger-mobile"></div>
</div>
<div id="block-mainpagecontent">
  
    
      <article role="article" class="presidential-speech">

  
    

  <div class="ps-container video-container">
    <div class="presidential-speeches--sidebar">
      
<div  class="about-this-episode">
    <h3>About this speech</h3>
      
<div  class="about-this-episode--inner">
      
            <p class="president-name">John F. Kennedy</p>
      
            <p class="episode-date">April 20, 1961</p>
      
  <div class="speech-location-container">
    <span class="speech-label">Location</span>
              <span class="speech-loc">National Archives</span>
          </div>

            <div class="about-sidebar--intro"><p>In this written message, President John F. Kennedy discusses the importance of the American tax system and the many essential services funded by tax revenue. He proposes reforming the tax system to make it simpler and more equitable to all people. The President writes that paying taxes is the "annual price of citizenship." A few days after this message, President Kennedy became the first U.S. President to visit the Internal Revenue Service headquarters in Washington, D.C. After being introduced by IRS Commissioner Mortimer M. Caplin, Kennedy spoke to a gathering of IRS employees. <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uwx1II9T6Sg">To watch a video of the speech he gave during his visit, click here</a>.</p>
</div>
      
  </div>
  </div>
    </div>

    <div class="presidential-speeches--body-wrapper">
     <a href="/the-presidency/presidential-speeches" class="back-to-listing--cta">Presidential Speeches</a> <span class="nav-separator">|</span> <label class="presidential-speeches--label">John F. Kennedy Presidency</label>
      <h2 class="presidential-speeches--title"><span>April 20, 1961: Special Message to the Congress on Taxation</span>
</h2>
      
<div  class="presidential-speeches--body">
